Would you like me to compare this with the Oregon Enhanced HMO or discuss the specific benefits in more detail?`;
  }

  // Check for specific HSA Standard questions
  if (lowerMessage.includes('standard hsa') || lowerMessage.includes('hsa 3500') || lowerMessage.includes('standard hsa 3500') || lowerMessage.includes('hsa standard plan')) {
    return `Great question about the Standard HSA plan! This is a high-deductible health plan with excellent tax advantages. Here's the complete analysis:

**💰 Standard HSA Plan Analysis ($3,500 Deductible):**

**Plan Overview:**
• **Plan Type**: High Deductible Health Plan (HDHP)
• **Deductible**: $3,500 individual / $7,000 family
• **HSA Eligibility**: Yes - can contribute to Health Savings Account
• **Coverage Period**: 10/01/2024 - 12/31/2025

**HSA Tax Advantages:**
• **Pre-Tax Contributions** - Reduce taxable income
• **Tax-Free Growth** - Interest and investments grow tax-free
• **Tax-Free Withdrawals** - For qualified medical expenses
• **Triple Tax Advantage** - Only HSA offers this benefit

**Coverage Structure:**
• **Preventive Care**: 100% covered (no deductible)
• **Other Services**: Pay full cost until deductible met
• **After Deductible**: Usually 80-90% coverage
• **Out-of-Pocket Maximum**: $7,000 individual / $14,000 family

**HSA Contribution Limits (2024):**
• **Individual**: $4,300 maximum
• **Family**: $8,550 maximum
• **Catch-up (55+)**: Additional $1,000
• **Employer Contributions**: May contribute on your behalf

**Cost Analysis:**
• **Lower Premiums** - Significantly less than PPO
• **Higher Deductible** - Pay more out-of-pocket initially
• **HSA Savings** - Tax benefits can offset costs
• **Long-term Value** - HSA funds roll over year to year

**Best For:**
• Young, healthy individuals
• People who want to save for future healthcare
• Those comfortable with higher deductibles
• Tax-savvy individuals

**HSA Investment Options:**
• **Cash Account** - FDIC insured, no risk
• **Investment Options** - Mutual funds, ETFs
• **Growth Potential** - Long-term wealth building
• **Retirement Planning** - HSA becomes like 401k at 65

Would you like me to compare this with the Enhanced HSA plan or discuss HSA investment strategies?`;
  }

  // Check for specific HSA Enhanced questions
  if (lowerMessage.includes('enhanced hsa') || lowerMessage.includes('hsa 2000') || lowerMessage.includes('enhanced hsa 2000') || lowerMessage.includes('hsa enhanced plan')) {
    return `Excellent choice! The Enhanced HSA plan offers the best of both worlds - HSA tax advantages with a lower deductible. Here's the complete analysis:

**💰 Enhanced HSA Plan Analysis ($2,000 Deductible):**

**Plan Overview:**
• **Plan Type**: High Deductible Health Plan (HDHP)
• **Deductible**: $2,000 individual / $4,000 family
• **HSA Eligibility**: Yes - can contribute to Health Savings Account
• **Coverage Period**: 10/01/2024 - 12/31/2025

**Enhanced Benefits (vs Standard HSA):**
• **Lower Deductible** - $1,500 less than Standard HSA
• **Faster Coverage** - Reach coverage threshold sooner
• **Better for Families** - Lower family deductible
• **Same HSA Benefits** - All tax advantages maintained

**HSA Tax Advantages:**
• **Pre-Tax Contributions** - Reduce taxable income
• **Tax-Free Growth** - Interest and investments grow tax-free
• **Tax-Free Withdrawals** - For qualified medical expenses
• **Triple Tax Advantage** - Only HSA offers this benefit

**Coverage Structure:**
• **Preventive Care**: 100% covered (no deductible)
• **Other Services**: Pay full cost until deductible met
• **After Deductible**: Usually 80-90% coverage
• **Out-of-Pocket Maximum**: $6,000 individual / $12,000 family

**HSA Contribution Limits (2024):**
• **Individual**: $4,300 maximum
• **Family**: $8,550 maximum
• **Catch-up (55+)**: Additional $1,000
• **Employer Contributions**: May contribute on your behalf

**Cost Analysis:**
• **Higher Premiums** - More than Standard HSA
• **Lower Deductible** - Pay less out-of-pocket initially
• **HSA Savings** - Tax benefits can offset costs
• **Better Value** - For moderate healthcare users

**Best For:**
• People who want HSA benefits with lower deductible
• Families with moderate healthcare needs
• Those who want faster coverage activation
• Tax-savvy individuals who use healthcare regularly

**HSA Investment Options:**
• **Cash Account** - FDIC insured, no risk
• **Investment Options** - Mutual funds, ETFs
• **Growth Potential** - Long-term wealth building
• **Retirement Planning** - HSA becomes like 401k at 65

Would you like me to compare this with the Standard HSA plan or discuss HSA contribution strategies?`;
  }

  // Check for specific PPO questions
  if (lowerMessage.includes('ppo plan') || lowerMessage.includes('preferred provider') || lowerMessage.includes('ppo coverage') || lowerMessage.includes('ppo benefits')) {
    return `Great question about the PPO plan! This offers the most flexibility in provider choice. Here's the complete analysis:

**🏥 PPO Plan Analysis (Preferred Provider Organization):**

**Plan Overview:**
• **Plan Type**: Preferred Provider Organization
• **Network Flexibility**: In-network and out-of-network coverage
• **Referral Requirements**: None - direct access to specialists
• **Coverage Period**: 10/01/2024 - 12/31/2025

**PPO Advantages:**
• **Provider Choice** - See any doctor you want
• **No Referrals** - Direct access to specialists
• **Out-of-Network** - Coverage even outside network
• **Flexibility** - Change providers anytime

**Coverage Structure:**
• **In-Network**: Higher coverage (usually 80-90%)
• **Out-of-Network**: Lower coverage (usually 60-70%)
• **Deductible**: Usually $500-$1,500 individual
• **Coinsurance**: Percentage you pay after deductible

**Cost Analysis:**
• **Higher Premiums** - Most expensive option
• **Lower Deductibles** - Coverage kicks in sooner
• **Out-of-Network Costs** - Higher out-of-pocket
• **Value** - Best for people who want choice

**Best For:**
• People who want provider choice
• Those with specific doctors they want to keep
• People who travel frequently
• Those who want direct specialist access

**Network Benefits:**
• **In-Network**: Lower costs, better coverage
• **Out-of-Network**: Higher costs, but still covered
• **No Referrals** - See specialists directly
• **Flexibility** - Change providers anytime

**Coverage Highlights:**
• **Preventive Care**: 100% covered in-network
• **Emergency Care**: Covered anywhere
• **Prescription Drugs**: Tiered copay system
• **Mental Health**: Comprehensive coverage

Would you like me to compare this with the HSA plans or discuss the specific cost differences?`;
  }

  // Check for specific Northern CA DHMO questions
  if (lowerMessage.includes('northern ca') || lowerMessage.includes('northern california') || lowerMessage.includes('dhmo 500') || lowerMessage.includes('dhmo 2k') || lowerMessage.includes('northern ca dhmo')) {
    return `Excellent question about the Northern California DHMO plans! You have two great options. Here's the complete analysis:

**🌍 Northern California DHMO Plans Analysis:**

**Plan Options:**
• **DHMO $500 Plan** - Lower deductible, higher premiums
• **DHMO $2K Plan** - Higher deductible, lower premiums
• **Coverage Area**: Northern California specific
• **Plan Type**: Dental Health Maintenance Organization

**DHMO $500 Plan:**
• **Deductible**: $500 individual / $1,000 family
• **Copay**: $20 for most services
• **Premiums**: Higher monthly cost
• **Best For**: People who use dental services regularly

**DHMO $2K Plan:**
• **Deductible**: $2,000 individual / $4,000 family
• **Copay**: $20 for most services
• **Premiums**: Lower monthly cost
• **Best For**: People who want lower premiums

**DHMO Features:**
• **Network Only** - Must use designated providers
• **No Referrals** - Direct access to specialists
• **Lower Costs** - Reduced premiums and copays
• **Preventive Focus** - Emphasis on regular checkups

**Typical DHMO Benefits:**
• **Cleanings & Exams**: Usually 100% covered
• **Basic Procedures**: 80-90% coverage
